desc: A global radio service from UNICEF focusing on the health, education, equality and protection of children. Hosted by Blue Chevigny with UNICEF correspondents. Topics include education for girls, disaster preparedness in Asia and climate change.
name: UNICEF Podcast

desc: Featuring expert humanitarian practitioners from around the world, this podcast explores contemporary challenges to the application of humanitarian assistance. It is produced by The Advanced Training Program on Humanitarian Action.
name: Humanitarian Policy and Conflict Research

desc: This weekly program is your connection to tips, news, information and field interviews on major disasters. It covers both natural and man-made incidents, providing the information you need to better prepare for future responses.
name: Disaster Podcast

desc: TinySpark investigates philanthropy, nonprofits and international aid. In-depth interviews and shoe leather reporting from across the globe. The program also voices from the world of philanthropy, international aid and development.
name: Tiny Spark

desc: Terms of Reference is run by Aidpreneur.com, an online community for development and humanitarian aid professionals. The podcast delivers critical, insider information for top performance as a professional or organization in the social impact sector.
name: Terms of Reference Podcast

desc: This Week in Global Health (TWiGH) is a weekly show where Dr. Greg Martin and a team of qualified health experts, students and young professionals) give a brief overview of related current events and topics.
name: This Week in Global Health

desc: Working with those in the CDAC Network who respond to disasters and who believe that listening to those affected is the right and effective way to go. Run by a former BBC foreign correspondent and UNICEF worker in Africa and South Asia
name: AidDrops

desc: The official podcast of the ICRC in the US & Canada. It aims to highlight the human element behind the consequences of conflict, and features humanitarian profiles, operational updates, legal debates and discussions.
name: Intercross the Podcast

desc: In this podcast, Australian Red Cross aid workers talk about the challenges of providing aid – in the crises that make the news and the ones that don’t. If you’ve ever donated to an aid agency or wanted to be an aid worker, this is the show for you.
name: How Aid Works

desc: UN Radio covers the activities of the United Nations from its headquarters in New York and from around the world. Episodes range from individual news and feature stories to presenter-led daily and weekly current affairs programmes.
name: United Nations Radio

desc: Why do wars have laws? What do they mean for today’s armed conflicts? How do these laws affect humanitarian agencies, armed forces, prisoners and non-combatants? Eminent academics and lawyers unpack the laws of war, drawing on examples from Syria to South Sudan.
name: Laws of War

desc: Learning sessions and webinars organized by the International Association of Professionals in Humanitarian Assistance and Protection. Open to members and the wider humanitarian community, this podcast covers a wide range of humanitarian issues from financing to coordination.
name: PHAP: Learning Sessions and Webinars

desc: Listen to the ideas and opinions of respected voices from across the international development field - on a wide range of subjects from climate change to health and education, from economic growth and trade to democracy and accountability.
name: DFID Podcast

desc: AidData presents a six-episode podcast series to take you past the maps and dashboards on our website to the human stories at the heart of their research. Topics include  disaster response, tracking aid flows, nutrition, and women's empowerment.
name: Deeper Than Data

desc: Listen to the World's top economists discuss their research and deconstruct global economic trends. Topics range from the impact of financial technology to the effects of hunger and climate change. Episodes feature high-level experts such as professors and public officials.
name: IMF Podcasts

desc: International development experts share their ideas on how wealthy countries can promote prosperity in developing countries. Topics range from immigration to climate change and feature high-level officials from governments and internatoinal organizations.
name: CGD Podcast

desc: This podcast explores the key issues affecting billions of people across the developing world. Recent editions have looked at why 75 million of the world’s poorest children can’t access education and why big data offers new tools to help countries meet their development goals.
name: Global Development

desc: This podcast is a weekly look at global health and the fight against poverty, hosted by journalist Tom Paulson, a veteran journalist who for more than a quarter century has covered matters of global health, science, medicine, health policy, aid and development.
name: Humanosphere Podcast

desc: Hear from leading representatives from the worlds of politics, diplomacy, academia, business, civil society, the military and the media. During each of their conferences they take the opportunity to talk with some of the key opinion formers about the issues at hand.
name: Wilton Park Dialogues

desc: This podcast higlights the news, issues, events and trends in international development and relief work. The series will address some of the most complex issues in global health, which affect millions of people around the globe.
name: Global Health Checkup

desc: This human rights prodcast airs weekly from the Centre of Governance and Human Rights. Tune in each Monday as their panel explores the rights and wrongs of contemporary politics, joined by fascinating guests from the University of Cambridge and around the world.
name: Declarations: The Human Rights Podcast

desc: The Refugee Studies Centre (RSC) aims to build knowledge and understanding of the causes and effects of forced migration in order to help improve the lives of some of the world's most vulnerable people. Podcasts include public seminars, conferences, and book launches.
name: Refugee Studies

desc: COMPAS conducts high quality research in order to develop theory and knowledge, inform policy-making and public debate, and engage users of research within the field of migration. Topics include the Mediterranean migrant crises, migratation in the media, xenophobia, and more.
name: Centre of Migration, Policy, and Society (COMPAS)

desc: Keep up with the latest trends and issues in the movement of people worldwide. IMI analyses migration as an intrinsic part of broader global transformation processes rather than a problem to be solved. Topics covered include migratory flows, gender-based violence, remittances, and more.
name: International Migration Institute

desc: MPI is a nonprofit, nonpartisan think tank dedicated to the study of the movement of people worldwide (immigration, migration). Among others, topics include immigrant integration, immigration policy, and refugees, IDPs, and humanitarian response.
name: Migration Policy Institute Podcasts

desc: Long form interviews with foreign policy influencers, and deep discussions with experts on topical issues in global affairs. Recent coverage includes topics such as conflict in the Horn of Africa, peace in Colombia, and how to get a job in the United Nations.
name: Global Dispatches -- Conversations on Foreign Policy and World Affairs

desc: Listen to events at Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs. Speakers include authors, government and UN officials, economists, policymakers, and businesspeople. Topics range from the ethics of war and peace to issues at the forefront of global social justice.
name: Carnegie Council Audio Podcast

desc: Lectures by humanitarian and human rights professionals from across the world, who analyze human rights issues through various lens such as gender, law, economics, etc. The Raoul Wallenberg Institute works to enhance the rights and protection of the millions of refugees and migrants at risk.
name: On Human Rights
